I just realized that the atomic boolean is not sufficient to synchronize between
```java
010 Iterator.close() {
020  if (!isAborted.get()) {
030    isAborted.set(true);
040    queue.clear();
050    queue.add(poison);
060  }
070 }
080 // and
090 Destination.receive(chunk) {
100  if (!isAborted.get() {
110    queue.add(chunk);
120  }
130 }
```
The issue arises in the following situation:

- Parser thread is not aborted and passes the test in 100 and is now just about to run 110 which would add a chunk.
- Meanwhile, the close thread executes 020 up to 040 - so isAborted is set to true and the queue is cleared.
- Parser finally executes 110 and adds another chunk to the freshly cleared queue.
- Closer executes 050 and adds the poison after the chunk.

Effect: the client iterator will yield garbage data from somewhere down the element stream.

